   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Day 5: DuckDB — Zero-Config Analytics on Files\n",
    "\n",
    "## Objective\n",
    "Discover why DuckDB is called \"SQLite for analytics.\" You will:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Import DuckDB and see how simple setup is compared to PostgreSQL\n",
    "2. Query CSV files directly — no loading, no schema definition\n",
    "3. Convert CSV to Parquet and query it with DuckDB\n",
    "4. Run the same queries from Days 1-4 on DuckDB (SQL is nearly identical)\n",
    "5. Use `DESCRIBE` to see auto-detected schemas\n",
    "6. Use `SUMMARIZE` for instant statistical summaries\n",
    "7. Join across multiple CSV files\n",
    "8. Read multiple files with glob patterns\n",
    "9. Export query results to Parquet\n",
    "10. Compare CSV vs Parquet performance\n",
    "11. Try It Yourself exercises\n",
    "\n",
    "## Table of Contents\n",
    "1. [Import and Setup](#1-import-and-setup)\n",
    "2. [Query CSV Directly](#2-query-csv-directly)\n",
    "3. [CSV to Parquet](#3-csv-to-parquet)\n",
    "4. [Same Queries as PostgreSQL](#4-same-queries-as-postgresql)\n",
    "5. [DESCRIBE — Auto-Detected Schema](#5-describe--auto-detected-schema)\n",
    "6. [SUMMARIZE — Instant Statistics](#6-summarize--instant-statistics)\n",
    "7. [Join Across Files](#7-join-across-files)\n",
    "8. [Glob Patterns](#8-glob-patterns)\n",
    "9. [Export to Parquet](#9-export-to-parquet)\n",
    "10. [Performance: CSV vs Parquet](#10-performance-csv-vs-parquet)\n",
    "11. [Try It Yourself](#11-try-it-yourself)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Import and Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "With PostgreSQL we needed:\n",
    "- A running server process\n",
    "- A database and user created with `CREATE DATABASE` / `CREATE USER`\n",
    "- `psycopg2.connect()` with host, port, user, password\n",
    "- Tables created with `CREATE TABLE` before loading any data\n",
    "\n",
    "With DuckDB? Just import and go. There is no server, no users, no configuration."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import duckdb\n",
    "\n",
    "# That's it. No connection string, no server, no setup.\n",
    "# duckdb.sql() runs a query on an in-memory database and returns the result.\n",
    "print(duckdb.sql(\"SELECT 'Hello from DuckDB!' AS greeting\"))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "DuckDB is embedded — it runs inside the Python process, just like SQLite. But unlike SQLite (which is optimized for OLTP), DuckDB is built for **analytical queries**: aggregations, window functions, large scans."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Query CSV Directly\n",
    "\n",
    "DuckDB can read CSV files without any setup. No `CREATE TABLE`, no schema definition, no data loading. Just point it at a file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "duckdb.sql(\"SELECT * FROM 'data/employees.csv' LIMIT 10\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "DuckDB automatically:\n",
    "- Detected column names from the header row\n",
    - Inferred data types (INTEGER, VARCHAR, DOUBLE, DATE, BOOLEAN)\n",
    - Parsed the CSV format\n",
    "\n",
    "In PostgreSQL this would have required: `CREATE TABLE`, then `COPY ... FROM`, then the query."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. CSV to Parquet\n",
    "\n",
    "Parquet is a columnar file format optimized for analytics. DuckDB reads Parquet natively. Let's convert our CSV to Parquet using pandas + pyarrow, then query it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "# Read CSV with pandas\n",
    "df_employees = pd.read_csv('data/employees.csv')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Save as Parquet (using pyarrow engine under the hood)\n",
    "df_employees.to_parquet('data/employees.parquet', index=False)\n",
    "print('Parquet file created: data/employees.parquet')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Query the Parquet file with DuckDB\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"SELECT * FROM 'data/employees.parquet' LIMIT 10\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Verify both sources produce identical results\n",
    "csv_result = duckdb.sql(\"SELECT * FROM 'data/employees.csv' ORDER BY emp_id\").fetchall()\n",
    "parquet_result = duckdb.sql(\"SELECT * FROM 'data/employees.parquet' ORDER BY emp_id\").fetchall()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"CSV rows:     {len(csv_result)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Parquet rows: {len(parquet_result)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Results match: {csv_result == parquet_result}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Identical results, but as we will see in Section 10, Parquet is significantly faster to query."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Same Queries as PostgreSQL\n",
    "\n",
    "The SQL you learned in Days 1-4 works in DuckDB with almost no changes. DuckDB supports:\n",
    "- Standard `SELECT`, `WHERE`, `GROUP BY`, `HAVING`, `ORDER BY`\n",
    "- All JOIN types: `INNER JOIN`, `LEFT JOIN`, `RIGHT JOIN`, `FULL OUTER JOIN`, `CROSS JOIN`\n",
    "- Window functions: `ROW_NUMBER()`, `RANK()`, `DENSE_RANK()`, `SUM() OVER (...)`\n",
    "- CTEs (`WITH` clauses)\n",
    "- String functions, date functions, `CASE` expressions\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.1 Basic SELECT with WHERE and ORDER BY"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Same query we ran on PostgreSQL: find high earners\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"\"\"\n",
    "    SELECT first_name, last_name, salary, hire_date\n",
    "    FROM 'data/employees.csv'\n",
    "    WHERE salary > 90000\n",
    "    ORDER BY salary DESC\n",
    "\"\"\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.2 GROUP BY with Aggregations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Average salary by department — identical SQL to PostgreSQL\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"\"\"\n",
    "    SELECT\n",
    "        department_id,\n",
    "        COUNT(*) AS num_employees,\n",
    "        ROUND(AVG(salary), 2) AS avg_salary,\n",
    "        MIN(salary) AS min_salary,\n",
    "        MAX(salary) AS max_salary\n",
    "    FROM 'data/employees.csv'\n",
    "    GROUP BY department_id\n",
    "    ORDER BY avg_salary DESC\n",
    "\"\"\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.3 Window Functions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Rank employees by salary within each department — same SQL as PostgreSQL\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"\"\"\n",
    "    SELECT\n",
    "        first_name,\n",
    "        last_name,\n",
    "        department_id,\n",
    "        salary,\n",
    "        RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY department_id ORDER BY salary DESC) AS salary_rank,\n",
    "        ROUND(AVG(salary) OVER (PARTITION BY department_id), 2) AS dept_avg_salary\n",
    "    FROM 'data/employees.csv'\n",
    "    ORDER BY department_id, salary_rank\n",
    "\"\"\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.4 CTEs (WITH clauses)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Using a CTE to find employees above department average salary\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"\"\"\n",
    "    WITH dept_stats AS (\n",
    "        SELECT\n",
    "            department_id,\n",
    "            AVG(salary) AS avg_salary\n",
    "        FROM 'data/employees.csv'\n",
    "        GROUP BY department_id\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    SELECT\n",
    "        e.first_name,\n",
    "        e.last_name,\n",
    "        e.department_id,\n",
    "        e.salary,\n",
    "        ROUND(d.avg_salary, 2) AS dept_avg,\n",
    "        ROUND(e.salary - d.avg_salary, 2) AS diff_from_avg\n",
    "    FROM 'data/employees.csv' AS e\n",
    "    JOIN dept_stats AS d ON e.department_id = d.department_id\n",
    "    WHERE e.salary > d.avg_salary\n",
    "    ORDER BY diff_from_avg DESC\n",
    "\"\"\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice: the SQL is **nearly identical** to what we wrote for PostgreSQL. The same skills transfer directly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. DESCRIBE — Auto-Detected Schema\n",
    "\n",
    "In PostgreSQL, you would run `\\d employees` or query `information_schema.columns`. In DuckDB, just use `DESCRIBE` on the file query."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "duckdb.sql(\"DESCRIBE SELECT * FROM 'data/employees.csv'\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "DuckDB detected:\n",
    "- `emp_id` as INTEGER\n",
    - `first_name`, `last_name`, `email` as VARCHAR\n",
    - `department_id` as INTEGER\n",
    "- `salary` as DOUBLE\n",
    "- `hire_date` as DATE\n",
    "- `manager_id` as DOUBLE (because it contains NULLs)\n",
    "- `is_active` as BOOLEAN\n",
    "\n",
    "No schema file, no DDL statements — DuckDB figured it all out from the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. SUMMARIZE — Instant Statistical Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a DuckDB superpower. `SUMMARIZE` gives you count, mean, std, min, max, and approximate quantiles for every column in a single command. In pandas, this is `df.describe()`. In PostgreSQL, you would need multiple aggregation queries."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "duckdb.sql(\"SUMMARIZE SELECT * FROM 'data/employees.csv'\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In one query we can see:\n",
    "- Salary ranges from 62,000 to 145,000\n",
    "- Hire dates span from 2017 to 2024\n",
    "- Most employees are active (TRUE vs FALSE counts)\n",
    "- Missing values in `manager_id` (the top-level managers have no manager)\n",
    "\n",
    "This is incredibly useful for exploratory data analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Join Across Files\n",
    "\n",
    "DuckDB can join tables that live in separate files — no need to load them into a database first."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Join employees with departments — two separate CSV files\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"\"\"\n",
    "    SELECT\n",
    "        e.first_name,\n",
    "        e.last_name,\n",
    "        e.salary,\n",
    "        d.dept_name,\n",
    "        d.location\n",
    "    FROM 'data/employees.csv' AS e\n",
    "    JOIN 'data/departments.csv' AS d ON e.department_id = d.dept_id\n",
    "    ORDER BY d.dept_name, e.salary DESC\n",
    "\"\"\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In PostgreSQL, both tables would need to exist in the database. In DuckDB, they are just files on disk."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8. Glob Patterns\n",
    "\n",
    "DuckDB supports glob patterns to read multiple files at once. This is powerful when your data is split across files (e.g., one file per month, per region, etc.).\n",
    "\n",
    "Our CSV files all have different schemas, so reading them all together will show DuckDB's union-by-name behavior. A more realistic example would be multiple files with the same schema."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Read all CSV files in the data directory\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"SELECT * FROM 'data/*.csv' LIMIT 15\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When all files share the same schema (like monthly sales files), glob patterns let you query them as one table. DuckDB stacks the files and treats them as a single dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9. Export to Parquet\n",
    "\n",
    "DuckDB can export query results directly to Parquet files with the `COPY` command."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Export a joined, aggregated result to Parquet\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"\"\"\n",
    "    COPY (\n",
    "        SELECT\n",
    "            d.dept_name,\n",
    "            d.location,\n",
    "            COUNT(*) AS num_employees,\n",
    "            ROUND(AVG(e.salary), 2) AS avg_salary,\n",
    "            MIN(e.salary) AS min_salary,\n",
    "            MAX(e.salary) AS max_salary\n",
    "        FROM 'data/employees.csv' AS e\n",
    "        JOIN 'data/departments.csv' AS d ON e.department_id = d.dept_id\n",
    "        GROUP BY d.dept_name, d.location\n",
    "        ORDER BY avg_salary DESC\n",
    "    ) TO 'data_output/department_summary.parquet' (FORMAT PARQUET)\n",
    "\"\"\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print('Exported to data_output/department_summary.parquet')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Verify the exported file\n",
    "duckdb.sql(\"SELECT * FROM 'data_output/department_summary.parquet'\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `COPY ... TO` command is the same syntax as PostgreSQL. Another familiar pattern that transfers directly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 10. Performance: CSV vs Parquet\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's time the same query on a CSV file vs a Parquet file. Even with our small dataset, Parquet should be faster because:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Columnar storage**: Parquet stores data by column, so the query only reads the columns it needs (salary, department_id). CSV requires reading every byte of every row.\n",
    "2. **Compression**: Parquet compresses data, reducing I/O.\n",
    "3. **Statistics**: Parquet files contain min/max statistics per row group, allowing DuckDB to skip entire blocks that do not match the filter.\n",
    "4. **No parsing**: CSV requires text parsing (splitting on commas, handling quotes). Parquet is binary — no parsing overhead.\n",
    "\n",
    "The performance difference grows **dramatically** with larger datasets. On gigabyte-scale data, Parquet can be 10-100x faster."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import time\n",
    "\n",
    "# Our test query: GROUP BY + window function\n",
    "query = \"\"\"\n",
    "    SELECT\n",
    "        department_id,\n",
    "        COUNT(*) AS num_employees,\n",
    "        ROUND(AVG(salary), 2) AS avg_salary,\n",
    "        RANK() OVER (ORDER BY AVG(salary) DESC) AS dept_rank\n",
    "    FROM {source}\n",
    "    GROUP BY department_id\n",
    "    ORDER BY avg_salary DESC\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "# Time CSV\n",
    "csv_times = []\n",
    "for i in range(5):\n",
    "    start = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    duckdb.sql(query.format(source=\"'data/employees.csv'\")).fetchall()\n",
    "    csv_times.append(time.perf_counter() - start)\n",
    "avg_csv = sum(csv_times) / len(csv_times)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Time Parquet\n",
    "parquet_times = []\n",
    "for i in range(5):\n",
    "    start = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    duckdb.sql(query.format(source=\"'data/employees.parquet'\")).fetchall()\n",
    "    parquet_times.append(time.perf_counter() - start)\n",
    "avg_parquet = sum(parquet_times) / len(parquet_times)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"CSV avg time:     {avg_csv*1000:.2f} ms\")\n",
    "print(f\"Parquet avg time: {avg_parquet*1000:.2f} ms\")\n",
    "print(f\"Parquet is {avg_csv/avg_parquet:.1f}x faster\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "With this tiny dataset the difference might be modest (a few milliseconds). But imagine a file with 10 million rows:\n",
    "\n",
    "- CSV: DuckDB must parse ~500 MB of text, split every line on commas, convert strings to numbers.\n",
    "- Parquet: DuckDB reads only the needed columns directly as binary numbers, skipping irrelevant row groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is why data engineers convert raw CSV/JSON to Parquet as the first step in any pipeline."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 11. Try It Yourself\n",
